[{"id":27231,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Hzqs6XmRkP3DMBOEymvWEY39VMFEE332kuquVTy5c3I.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/NrUis3lLp2_7eX-ytYmW4dqMFwjW9oBu_obzohhUhOA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yc_N02L-ogmb2wbS8nKQu1-FJ0aVVSGdngMxVcz2jFw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/TiyAL0mSfx7hgeOc04U2PZP7qwR6hc5Duejckmzdy6k.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9CKrAXTiPbAwCLL2Vmy8eAiqv9n-XTjsM1Q6ZwuI4gg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27269,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Products in the given reactions are as&nbsp;follows:</p><p>1.&nbsp;Hoffmann bromamide degradation is useful in the production of aniline as it converts the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CONH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;functional group into the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group.&nbsp;So, we need to take a starting material that has the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CONH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group and after getting converted into&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group, the molecule obtained is aniline. So, in order to obtain aniline as the final product, we require Benzamide as a starting material.&nbsp;So, in this way, we can easily convert Benzamide to Aniline.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3b3bad20-6680-447a-97a4-3f7bd238d279-9896183.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 105px;\" /></p><p>2. Gabriel phthalimide synthesis cannot be used to prepare aniline because aryl halides do not give&nbsp;Gabriel phthalimide reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/01dc03c0-9049-46a0-9d62-995e7b892caa-image.png\" style=\"width: 321px; height: 130px;\" /></p><p>3. When nitrobenzene&nbsp;is reacted with an active metal like Pd/C and H<sub>2</sub><sub>,</sub>&nbsp;&nbsp;it produces aniline. This reaction is also called Nitrobenzene reduction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/da2c02d8-7d00-40bb-97ff-e50f3bea7704-9896183_4.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 114px;\" /></p><p>4.&nbsp;When acetanilide&nbsp;is treated with dil.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>, it produces aniline.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Aromatic amines will be formed in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></math>.</p><p>So, answer is 3.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27280,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cc044442-fd5d-4836-a295-5dedbbabc086-image.png\" style=\"width: 172px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4229931a-5c9c-406b-808d-07ca83287fd6-image.png\" style=\"width: 195px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e2811cf9-a60d-4ae4-a296-9ee40b3c59a6-ad0a3e78-c151-4578-b54d-c69f0627d046-image.png\" style=\"width: 192px; height: 147px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/465e967b-f0b2-40b7-be2e-46802ea99986-image.png\" style=\"width: 177px; height: 150px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The first step of the reaction is nucleophilic substitution reaction in which ammonia being a strong nucleophile&nbsp;will substitute chloride ion and amide will be formed in place of acid chloride. In 2nd step Hoffmann degradation reaction will take place and will give aniline in place of amide.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6af9b737-da2c-4931-ba5c-f8fa20f079d9-6cc34cc1-bcf7-4dc1-89b3-93adc4fd0b2c-image.png\" style=\"width: 632px; height: 146px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27251,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bc6db938-26be-45a3-9823-2ee48c951f7f.png\" style=\"width: 504px; height: 44px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/448cde91-e1d6-4657-a751-54838a61e471.png\" style=\"width: 447px; height: 127px;\"/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/07c64d4f-4141-4977-8c55-be7b237be1e0.png\" style=\"width: 433px; height: 136px;\"/>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>CONH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>→</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>NaBr</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The Markovnikov Rule predicts the regiochemistry of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HX</mi></math> addition to unsymmetrically substituted alkenes. The halide component of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HX</mi></math> bonds preferentially at the more highly substituted carbon, whereas hydrogen prefers the carbon which already contains more hydrogen.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/72560526-edb1-4f0c-972a-749c7f33fea3.png\" style=\"width: 427px; height: 119px;\"/></p><p>By the reaction with<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> amine doesnot lose any carbon while producing alcohol.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mo>→</mo><mrow><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>-</mo><msup><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math></p><p>Cyclohexene undergo allylic substitution reaction with bromine in the presence of sunlight.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7e454d13-fa21-4b3e-a29d-b2b6e98b14a4.png\" style=\"width: 295px; height: 166px;\"/></p><p>In Hoffmann bromamide degradation amides give amines by loss of one carbon.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>CONH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>NaOH</mi><mover><mo>→</mo><mrow></mrow></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>NaBr</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27395,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{CN}$ and $3 \\mathrm{KCl}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CONH}_2$ and $3 \\mathrm{KCl}$","$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{NC}$ and $\\mathrm{K}_2 \\mathrm{CO}_3$","$\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{NC}$ and $3 \\mathrm{KCl}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"It is example of carbylamine reaction. so, the product will be $\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{NC}$ and $\\mathrm{KCl}$. \nHence, (D) is the correct answer.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":27211,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Benzene $\\xrightarrow{HNO_3/H_2SO_4}$ Nitrobenzene (P) $\\xrightarrow{Sn/HCl}$ Aniline (Q) $\\xrightarrow{(CH_3CO)_2O}$ Acetanilide (R)<br>R $\\xrightarrow{HNO_3/H_2SO_4}$ p-Nitroacetanilide (S) $\\xrightarrow{HCl/EtOH, \\Delta}$ p-Nitroaniline (T)<br>T = p-Nitroaniline ($O_2N-C_6H_4-NH_2$), molecular formula $C_6H_6N_2O_2$<br>Molar mass = $6(12) + 6(1) + 2(14) + 2(16) = 72 + 6 + 28 + 32 = 138$ g/mol<br>% N = $\\frac{28}{138} \\times 100 = 20.29\\%$<br>Nearest integer = 20","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27303,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Nitrobenzene converted into Aniline by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>Sn</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Fe</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>Pd</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo></math> Raney <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ni</mi><mo>.</mo></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27384,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<u><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/223_form_1396912133992_60_e_11461_04.jpg\" style=\"width: 129px; height: 170px;\" /></strong></u>","<u><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/223_form_1396912133992_60_e_11461_03.jpg\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 130px;\" /></strong></u>","<u><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/223_form_1396912133992_60_e_11461_02.jpg\" style=\"width: 126px; height: 158px;\" /></strong></u>","<u><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/223_form_1396912133992_60_e_11461_01.jpg\" style=\"width: 179px; height: 183px;\" /></strong></u>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img height=\"312\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1a2a9949-4c1b-42fe-937d-61880470c797-image.png\" width=\"457\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27313,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mover><mi>Cl</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></mover></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></mover><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ae4bd25e-0dae-495a-8f44-3b5cdc0b2b5e-image.png\" style=\"width: 135px; height: 73px;\" />","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7be66ae7-b21b-4b8d-bfa6-d24481e9dba4-image.png\" style=\"width: 415px; height: 97px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27366,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>i</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Alkyl halide undergoes&nbsp;nucleophilic substitution reaction. More nucleophilic nitrogen of amine group, more reactive will it be with alkyl halides.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Presence of electron-withdrawing group will decrease the nucleophilic character of amino group.</p><p>Hence the order of reactivity;</p><p><img height=\"160\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3c8544f3-97eb-463e-884d-c8b00f21371a-image.png\" width=\"375\" /></p><p><img height=\"202\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/54609d56-b5ae-4c1e-92db-6f8a77889113-image.png\" width=\"447\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27307,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ec2cd50c-540d-4330-81a5-0bf2a3240fb4-image.png\" style=\"width: 231px; height: 169px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ffa6b358-5bc7-4615-99fc-eb5a15aacb57-image.png\" style=\"width: 179px; height: 167px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4ac4f94f-9d5b-4b2f-81d9-89f7711d5c50-image.png\" style=\"width: 230px; height: 167px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a1deef86-09f6-4b66-8397-e134f04a09e4-image.png\" style=\"width: 229px; height: 181px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ded17863-9edd-45f3-a6f2-a5c4b66b47bf-image.png\" style=\"width: 690px; height: 208px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27234,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/CouClNxtYRxGiTKe_t26esrMNNKg82gWeHeU2VQi-yg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27235,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Primary amine give an ionic solid upon reaction with Hinsberg reagent which is soluble in $\\mathrm{NaOH}$.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/KeuW0mjnxpcx7J9rtPxJ9tpSx0yyNVR7xSHlVkAreCk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27311,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["Both (A) and (R) true but (R) is not the correct<br />&nbsp;explanation of (A).","(A) is false but ( R) is true.","Both (A) and (R)&nbsp;true and (R)&nbsp;is correct<br />explanation of (A).","(A) is true but (R)&nbsp;is false."],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Gabriel phthalimide synthesis</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f6e03060-2699-40a0-985c-d2a3e2032ed5-image.png\" style=\"width: 438px; height: 350px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27323,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/10a4f7f5-ac42-4798-ba6e-e75d90afa6b6-image.png\" style=\"width: 444px; height: 196px;\" /></p><p>no of moles<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mol</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27301,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e5663f80-aa37-41d0-aac2-70237ee916a5-image.png\" style=\"width: 155px; height: 112px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a0a5fb1a-43a9-4e87-9d53-bdf0fc7526ac-image.png\" style=\"width: 207px; height: 126px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9ce998f8-196c-4c06-84d4-fdf5aadc4eb1-92b68f09-ecff-4e9b-b744-957d05512e3c-image.png\" style=\"width: 164px; height: 112px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/57831ebc-3d8b-48c0-b23b-09d1edf1cd7a-9c83db3a-49d8-4306-8887-92166e55ddf2-image.png\" style=\"width: 99px; height: 158px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/86daf90f-81e4-4f8d-9ce7-34fd2cb7c364-7a08fdf0-1bd9-417e-b99e-1fc91bf85b7d-image.png\" style=\"width: 274px; height: 169px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27271,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["Ethylnitrile","Propylamine","Propanenitrile","Ethylamine"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>It is Hoffmann bromamide degradation reaction in which propanamide&nbsp;is converted to an ethylamine&nbsp;containing one carbon atom lesser than in the amide.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4f38f143-8475-441c-9974-08bc9b2ebac8-9895107.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 166px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27354,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5721debb-c0e3-42f5-b7b9-d10a4ea18c86-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 136px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3b6c2140-03fc-4ee9-8a03-64206bbd0edd-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 184px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e0bff514-4814-4d6d-9d4b-a1d2cbf75973-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 139px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6d273c8a-8b2c-47d4-9096-77a39e013f2b-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 139px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Aniline reacts with a mixture of sodium nitrite and hydrochloric acid and forms benzene diazonium chloride.The structure of Benzene diazonium chloride is</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/73f23034-1d2d-4a8d-8ccf-8106bae0d1fe2360436833253115460.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 183px;\" /></p><p>Benzene diazonium chloride reacts with aniline in presence of dilute hydrochloric acid and undergoes coupling reaction and produces stable azo products. In this reaction, benzene diazonium chloride acts as an electrophile in coupling with activated aniline. In this type of reaction, substitution takes place at the para position. So, the reaction Benzene diazonium chloride with aniline in presence of dilute hydrochloric acid is as follows:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0ec5bc6e-e016-409e-9c12-f00a40feb1b2-image5.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27333,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>When hydrogen atoms of the amino group of arylamines are replaced by electron donating alkyl groups, the basic character of the resulting amine increases.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4fabeda8-8134-41f2-86ee-000700d04295-image.png\" style=\"width: 380px; height: 177px;\" /></p><p>B.S. order,&nbsp;Phenyl methanamine &gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>-Dimethylaniline&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>-Methyl aniline &gt; Benzenamine.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27246,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but statement II is true","Both statement I and statement II are false","Statement I is true but statement II is false","Both statement I and statement II are true"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Aniline reacts with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>conc</mi><mo>.</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>followed by heating at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>453</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>473</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math>gives p-aminobenzene sulphonic acid, which gives blood red colour in the 'Lassaigne's test'Nitrogen, sulphur, and halogens present in organic compounds are detected by Lassaigne's test. Here, a small piece of Na metal is heated in a fusion tube with the organic compound. The principle is that, in doing so, Na converts all the elements present into ionic form.</p><p>Aniline does not undergo Friedel-Crafts reaction (alkylation and acetylation) due to salt formation with aluminium chloride, the Lewis acid, which is used as a catalyst. Due to this, nitrogen of aniline acquires positive charge and hence acts as a strong deactivating group for further reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bd43543a-f730-410a-bc33-f10b5ce6c646.png\" style=\"width: 1000px; height: 203px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27263,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/71134e92-6def-4dcc-ab8a-e8a8c9893f1e-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 100px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/27a57ebb-16fc-45ea-8110-81431d77fc44-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 110px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/30d39fe8-bc4f-4ccb-9794-5d6167a8e949-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 103px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0853e6a9-0b62-453e-8b82-f8263c0d3eca-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 112px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Acetanilide undergo electrophilic bromination&nbsp;with bromine in acetic acid. p-bromoacetaniide&nbsp;is the major product in this reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/434e5f51-0408-45f2-a37d-5872dc7f3721.png\" style=\"width: 441px; height: 191px;\" /></p><p>Acetanilide undergo reduction reaction with lithium aluminium hydride.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e2d0e5c5-49b2-4556-8da3-dc7598682cc1.png\" style=\"width: 427px; height: 172px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27208,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["3","5","6","1"],"answer":1,"solution":"The reaction sequence is as follows:<br>1. Bromination of nitrobenzene with $Br_2/FeBr_3$ results in meta-bromonitrobenzene because the $-NO_2$ group is meta-directing. (1 Br atom)<br>2. Reduction of the nitro group using $Sn/HCl$ followed by pH neutralization converts $-NO_2$ to $-NH_2$. The product is m-bromoaniline.<br>3. Reaction with $Br_2/H_2O$ (bromine water) on m-bromoaniline: The $-NH_2$ group is highly activating and ortho/para directing. In m-bromoaniline, the positions ortho and para to $-NH_2$ are vacant (positions 2, 4, and 6 relative to $-NH_2$). Bromine water causes polybromination at all available ortho and para positions. This adds 3 more bromine atoms. (Total 1 + 3 = 4 Br atoms)<br>4. Diazotization with $NaNO_2/HBr$ at $0-5^{\\circ}C$ converts the $-NH_2$ group into a diazonium salt $-N_2^+Br^-$.<br>5. Sandmeyer reaction with $CuBr/NaBr$ replaces the diazonium group with a bromine atom. (Total 4 + 1 = 5 Br atoms)<br>The final product (P) is 1,2,3,4,5-pentabromobenzene. Therefore, the number of bromine atoms in the final product is 5.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27399,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["< smiles>Nc1ccccc1 < /smiles>","< smiles>NCc1ccccc1 < /smiles>","< smiles>Cc1ccccc1N < /smiles>","< smiles>CNc1ccccc1 < /smiles>"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":27352,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/da723bb0-8f50-4cbe-bdf7-52ba4f70bea3.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0a98b156-6921-440d-a5e3-7d2729d863fd.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c4bdbb33-98ce-4d02-a3c0-3fa76c00b2a8.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c9dac0f9-0ecc-41d3-a79b-7fb484947c03.jpeg\">"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2aee18d1-b8fb-4cde-810a-5ceb964eb17e.jpeg\">","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27335,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/846cfbfb-25ac-403f-a9c7-9d9e912d1349-image.png\" style=\"width: 123px; height: 61px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/865dadfe-f9d9-44d9-8f49-8e577f30567b-image.png\" style=\"width: 123px; height: 61px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6ffb3bad-957d-4f73-8945-537c2d06eeec-image.png\" style=\"width: 94px; height: 61px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1f3661b9-cbd2-4994-ae82-5873ee98d327-image.png\" style=\"width: 95px; height: 57px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>CARBYL amine given by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math> amine</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3bea69d2-ef34-4d67-b191-85c2609b7904-image.png\" style=\"width: 326px; height: 76px;\" /></p><p>Carbylamine reaction can be used to identify primary amino group in a given organic compound.&nbsp;When primary amines are treated with chloroform and alcoholic KOH, they give isocyanides (carbylamines) having very unpleasant smell which can be easily detected.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27358,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Hinsberg reagent is also known as benzene sulfonyl chloride and used for detection of primary, secondary and tertiary amines. <br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/63bc47d6-cdf5-4b55-b6e4-14e75f3d234f-image35.png\">","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27268,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/68b150f1-0aca-41d0-969b-1f1a09352507-9896191_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 276px; height: 180px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7e660dad-ae2b-4edd-8434-2eeac95e2d81-9896191_3.PNG\" style=\"width: 279px; height: 180px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7715cc96-6b90-4637-bbad-c7e6d84f0ef6-9896191_2.PNG\" style=\"width: 319px; height: 180px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/db2fd976-b8ae-4f15-a0fd-bbb308160a3e-9896191_4.PNG\" style=\"width: 263px; height: 180px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Nitrobenzene is reduced to aniline by passing hydrogen gas in presence of finely divided palladium and also by reduction with metals in an acidic medium. When aniline reacts with acetic anhydride in the presence of pyridine to give acetanilide. Aniline acts as a weak base, while acetic anhydride acts as electrophile.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2b7527dd-14b3-4388-8439-e7523de0f7cc-9896191_5.PNG\" style=\"width: 503px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27285,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["Cumene","Benzenediazonium chloride","Benzal chloride","Ethylene glycol ketal"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>When an aromatic primary amine is treated with nitrous (NaNO<sub>2 </sub>+ HCl) acid at 273 &ndash; 278 K, diazonium salts are obtained. These diazonium salts&nbsp;are highly reactive in nature. Upon warming with water, these diazonium salts finally hydrolyze to phenols with the liberation of nitrogen gas. Phenols can also be obtained from diazonium salts by treating it with dilute acids.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/885ae620-3219-4cce-ad36-9462fd882dcc-image.png\" style=\"width: 330px; height: 120px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27195,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["2","5","4","8"],"answer":2,"solution":"Hinsberg's reagent (benzenesulfonyl chloride) classifies amines by their reaction products:<br>Primary amines (RNH₂) form alkali-soluble sulfonamides (soluble in NaOH).<br>Secondary amines (R₂NH) form alkali-insoluble sulfonamides (precipitate in NaOH).<br>Tertiary amines (R₃N) do not react.<br>Analyzing the given amines:<br>Aniline (primary), Methanamine (primary), Phenylmethanamine (primary), Allyl amine (primary), Isopropyl amine (primary) → alkali-soluble.<br>N,N-Dimethylmethanamine (tertiary), N,N-Dimethylaniline (tertiary) → no reaction.<br>N-Methylaniline (secondary), N-Methyl methanamine (secondary), N-Propylaniline (secondary), N-Phenylaniline (secondary) → alkali-insoluble.<br>Total alkali-insoluble sulfonamides: 4.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27212,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/eQrrY94vpZ4xsHa7_kM9k4jS1mvOibFFahe7thu8c5I.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gp2jaufF897C3-uzOKBffLTYtRKVR_vnngEusoIKEqM.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_YQj_tb7k5aEhpNdTqqd2Z5_b-lq_vTIkiVbCUEPsYg.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/zPcnQlNxXeb8xthdnbfWIUGDlr5G5JvSkJMBR2_CW2I.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/l85sGh2fdCpe-LWgwBLdF7sxMSJ05qT9GHs4fPkMT6I.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />A $\\rightarrow$ Benzamide Shows positive Lassaigh's test.<br />$B \\rightarrow$ Benzoic acid gives effervescence with aq.<br />$\\mathrm{NaHCO}_3$.<br />$\\mathrm{C} \\rightarrow$ Ester gives fruity smell.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (8 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27299,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<p>(i) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SOCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>(ii) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCN</mi></math></p><p>(iii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>Ni</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Na</mi><mfenced><mi>Hg</mi></mfenced><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math></p>","<p>(i) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math></p><p>(ii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>Ni</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Na</mi><mfenced><mi>Hg</mi></mfenced><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math></p>","<p>(i) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SOCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>(ii) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCN</mi></math></p><p>(iii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p>","<p>(i) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math></p><p>(ii)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Propyl alcohol&nbsp;undergo nucleophilic substitution reaction with thionyl chloride to give propyl chloride. Propyl chloride give butane nitrile on reaction with potasium cyanide. Butane nitrile on reduction give butyl amine.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ddb57688-e1a7-4b45-aeb4-26c994a1048d-3ae804f4-aeca-40e3-80ee-aec9125c09f9-image.png\" style=\"width: 469px; height: 147px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27398,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["benzylamine","aniline","acetanilide","p-nitroaniline"],"answer":0,"solution":"-NH2 group is not linked with benzene ring.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":27240,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/BUy9_UTl48C1lSKSgvSapQntINoGftNVMSxsJVGYLX0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Pok-HVtFRdTNUcm6jrQ4O1aYfjgGTj1v5a3U1ddn_jE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Yael4X7WA6iAGaI9HL9-NCJXmywuZtY3JBnpse7F1UY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/s-0gNS8FXcqCHlnEYoeONs44cR8mJY8Xb9Ren1O6KjA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1rXWS7dMKI4-HBlvzsOWV0MU7qJMtXA8PRvH2CDKFcs.original.fullsize.png\"><br />The above mechanism valid for both cis and trans isomers. So the products are same for both cis and trans isomers.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27278,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/114181eb-c89b-4bf2-b334-c7938b8c873f-image.png\" style=\"width: 158px; height: 130px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/210f99b1-7f98-4254-8cd3-426933d84695-image.png\" style=\"width: 179px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0df91e27-f61f-4a14-a275-d901d68c4a52-image.png\" style=\"width: 189px; height: 150px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e40e9b73-6cf7-4e7e-8bdc-a72d59073d68-image.png\" style=\"width: 313px; height: 130px;\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Benzenesulphonyl chloride <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Cl</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>, which is also known as Hinsberg&#39;s reagent, reacts with primary and secondary amines to form sulphonamides.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/811b7d10-f59f-4b27-b01d-f6382a3ed808-image.png\" style=\"width: 172px; height: 100px;\" /></p><p>The Hinsberg test is based on the production of sulfonamides. An amine interacts with benzene sulfonyl chloride in the Hinsberg test. Due to the inability of tertiary amines to form stable sulfonamides, any product produced is either a primary or secondary amine. If the resulting sulfonamide dissolves in aqueous sodium hydroxide solution, it is a primary amine. It is a secondary amine if the sulfonamide is insoluble in aqueous sodium hydroxide and hydrogen chloride.&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27270,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Amines","question":"","options":["A and D","Only B","A and B","B and C"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>When benzyl bromide is treated with AgCN, it forms&nbsp;benzyl isocyanide. This reaction is followed by the S<sub>N</sub><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;mechanism.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d5e448ea-9e15-4dba-a353-eabd991eb661-9895856_S1.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 158px;\" /></p><p>Benzylamine on heating with chloroform and ethanolic potassium hydroxide forms Benzyl&nbsp;isocyanides. &nbsp;This reaction is known as carbylamine reaction or isocyanide test.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fee9d791-3ca2-4fbf-b158-da374bcaec68-9895856_S2.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 153px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;amine does not give carbylamine&nbsp;reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0ed45165-0191-4cb6-b96f-0fae0159394d-336c83ed-8337-4c88-8a0e-11abd6d0f403-9895856_S3.png\" style=\"width: 559px; height: 117px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1ddd6e5b-bbc2-43c3-bbc5-18165898d165-9895856_S4.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 124px;\" />&nbsp;So, the correct option is C.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null}]